ance. Through an examination of a wide range of different care performances drawn from interdisciplinary and international settings, the book interrogates how performance might be understood as caring or uncaring, careless or careful, and correlatively how care can be conceptualised as artful, aesthetic, authentic or even 'fake' and 'staged'.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aArts. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Theater / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  aAesthetics of care.  aCare.  aDisability performance.  aEmotional labour.  aEthics.  aHealth.  aParticipatory theatre.  aPerformance.  aSocially-engaged.  aYoung people's theatre.1 aArcher-Martin, Jen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBaker, Sylvan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalvert, Dave, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeeny, Pat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFisher, Amanda Stuart, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGallagher, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHamington, Maurice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHouston, Sara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aInchley, Maggie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJennings, Matt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLloyd, Jayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcAvinchey, Caoimhe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aParry- Davies, Ella, econtributor.4ctb4https://i